@node @code{ebib-extras-attach-existing-file-action}
@section @code{ebib-extras-attach-existing-file-action}

@vindex ebib-extras-attach-existing-file-action
The user option @code{ebib-extras-attach-existing-file-action} controls what happens when @code{ebib-extras-attach-file} tries to install a file into a library directory where a file with the same name already exists (@ref{Attaching files}). This situation arises when you re-download a PDF or when two entries happen to share a key before one of them is regenerated.

The option accepts one of three values:

@itemize
@item
@code{nil}: abort the operation immediately and signal an error.
@item
@code{overwrite}: overwrite the existing file without prompting.
@item
@code{prompt} (the default): ask the user whether to overwrite.
@end itemize

The type is a choice between these three constants. In most workflows, the default value of @code{prompt} provides a good balance between safety and convenience. You may want to change it to @code{overwrite} if you frequently re-download files and trust that the newer version is always preferable, or to @code{nil} if you want strict protection against accidental overwrites.

