@node Opening associated files
@subsection Opening associated files

@findex ebib-extras-open-file-dwim
@findex ebib-extras-open-pdf-file
@findex ebib-extras-open-md-file
@findex ebib-extras-open-srt-file
@findex ebib-extras-open-vtt-file
@findex ebib-extras-open-webm-file
@findex ebib-extras-open-mp3-file
@findex ebib-extras-open-html-file
@findex ebib-extras-open-pdf-file-externally
@findex ebib-extras-open-html-file-externally
@findex ebib-extras-open-file
@findex ebib-extras-open-file-externally
A Bib@TeX{} entry often has several files attached to it---a PDF of the paper, an HTML snapshot, subtitle files for a video, or media files. The command @code{ebib-extras-open-file-dwim} provides a single entry point for opening whichever file is most relevant. It walks through the preference order defined in @code{ebib-extras-valid-file-extensions} (by default: PDF, HTML, WebM, FLAC, MP3, Markdown, SRT, VTT) and opens the first file it finds by calling the corresponding type-specific open command (@ref{File extension constants}).

For cases where you know exactly which file type you want, the package provides dedicated commands:

@itemize
@item
@code{ebib-extras-open-pdf-file} opens the PDF in Emacs using @code{find-file}.
@item
@code{ebib-extras-open-md-file} opens the Markdown file in Emacs.
@item
@code{ebib-extras-open-srt-file} opens the SRT subtitle file in Emacs.
@item
@code{ebib-extras-open-vtt-file} opens the VTT subtitle file in Emacs.
@item
@code{ebib-extras-open-html-file} opens the HTML file, renders it in @samp{eww}, and kills the raw HTML buffer afterward.
@item
@code{ebib-extras-open-webm-file} opens the WebM video file using the system's external application (via @samp{open}).
@item
@code{ebib-extras-open-mp3-file} opens the MP3 audio file externally.
@item
@code{ebib-extras-open-pdf-file-externally} opens the PDF using the system's default external PDF viewer.
@item
@code{ebib-extras-open-html-file-externally} opens the HTML file in the system's default browser.
@end itemize

The lower-level commands @code{ebib-extras-open-file} and @code{ebib-extras-open-file-externally} accept an extension as argument and are used by the type-specific wrappers above. They rely on @code{ebib-extras-get-file} to locate the file path from the entry's @samp{file} field (@ref{File retrieval}).

If no file with the requested extension is found, all of these commands signal a user error.

@node Attaching files
@subsection Attaching files

@findex ebib-extras-attach-file
@findex ebib-extras-attach-most-recent-file
The command @code{ebib-extras-attach-file} is the primary way to attach a file to a Bib@TeX{} entry. It accepts three optional arguments: FILE, KEY, and POSTPROCESS@. When called interactively, KEY defaults to the entry at point and POSTPROCESS is non-nil. The FILE argument determines where the source file comes from:

@itemize
@item
If FILE is @code{nil} (the default when called interactively without a prefix argument), the user is prompted to select a file, with completion over the downloads, PDF library, HTML library, and media library directories.
@item
If FILE is the symbol @code{most-recent} (activated by calling with a prefix argument, @samp{C-u}), the newest file in the downloads directory is used automatically.
@item
If FILE is a string, it is treated as the file path directly.
@end itemize

The file is renamed to @samp{KEY.EXT} and moved to the appropriate library directory based on its extension (@ref{File retrieval}). The entry's @samp{file} field is then updated. The command also calls @code{ebib-extras-set-abstract} to populate the abstract if it is empty (@ref{Entry processing and field manipulation}). When POSTPROCESS is non-nil and the attached file is a PDF, the command additionally writes PDF metadata (@ref{PDF metadata}), performs OCR, and opens the file.

The behavior when a file with the same name already exists at the destination is controlled by @code{ebib-extras-attach-existing-file-action} (@ref{@code{ebib-extras-attach-existing-file-action}}).

The convenience command @code{ebib-extras-attach-most-recent-file} calls @code{ebib-extras-attach-file} with the @code{most-recent} symbol, attaching the newest file from the downloads directory and post-processing it. This is useful after downloading a file from a browser.

@node Renaming and validating files
@subsection Renaming and validating files

@findex ebib-extras-rename-files
@findex ebib-extras-dedup-file-field
@findex ebib-extras-validate-file-stem
The command @code{ebib-extras-rename-files} renames all files listed in the @samp{file} field of the entry at point so that each file's base name matches the entry's Bib@TeX{} key. For example, if the entry key is @samp{Author2024Title} and the @samp{file} field contains @samp{some-random-name.pdf}, the file is renamed to @samp{Author2024Title.pdf} and moved to the appropriate library directory. The entry must have a valid key (@ref{Key validation}); otherwise, a user error is signaled.

The command @code{ebib-extras-dedup-file-field} removes duplicate file paths from the @samp{file} field of the current entry. Duplicates are detected by exact string comparison after trimming whitespace. The original order of first occurrences is preserved. This is useful after repeated attachment operations that may have added the same path more than once.

The function @code{ebib-extras-validate-file-stem} (not interactive) checks that every file listed in the @samp{file} field has a base name matching the entry's key. If any file does not match, a user error is signaled. This is used as a validation step in other workflows.

@node Managing invalid files
@subsection Managing invalid files

@findex ebib-extras-list-invalid-files
@findex ebib-extras-rename-next-invalid-file
Over time, library directories can accumulate files whose names do not correspond to any known Bib@TeX{} key. The command @code{ebib-extras-list-invalid-files} scans the PDF, HTML, and media library directories and populates the variable @code{ebib-extras-invalid-files} with all files whose base names fail a lookup against the bibliography via @code{tlon-bibliography-lookup}. This operation can be slow for large libraries because it checks every file.

Once the list is populated, the command @code{ebib-extras-rename-next-invalid-file} processes the first file in the list: it finds the corresponding Bib@TeX{} entry (using the filename to look up the key), opens the entry in Ebib, and calls @code{ebib-extras-rename-files} to correct the filename. The file is removed from @code{ebib-extras-invalid-files} after processing. Call this command repeatedly to work through the entire list of invalid files.

