@node Processing entries
@subsection Processing entries

@findex ebib-extras-process-entry
The command @code{ebib-extras-process-entry} provides a unified workflow for preparing a newly created or imported Bib@TeX{} entry. It performs the following steps in sequence:

@enumerate
@item
If the entry's key is invalid (does not match @code{ebib-extras-valid-key-regexp}), it regenerates the key via @code{ebib-generate-autokey}. If the key is already valid, it asks whether to regenerate it anyway.
@item
It sets or confirms the entry's language by calling @code{ebib-extras-get-or-set-language} (@ref{Language handling}).
@item
It calls @code{ebib-extras-attach-files} to download and attach the appropriate files based on available identifiers (@ref{Downloading and attaching from external sources}).
@end enumerate

This command assumes that the entry's type, author, date, and title fields are already correctly set.

@node Setting and fetching field values
@subsection Setting and fetching field values

@findex ebib-extras-copy-current-field-contents
@findex ebib-extras-sentence-case
@findex ebib-extras-update-field
@findex ebib-extras-set-abstract
@findex ebib-extras-set-id
@findex ebib-extras-no-translation-found
The command @code{ebib-extras-copy-current-field-contents} copies the value of the field at point to the kill ring. If the field's value comes from a cross-referenced entry, the resolved value is copied. This is a wrapper around @code{ebib-copy-field-contents} that automatically determines the current field.

The command @code{ebib-extras-sentence-case} converts the value of the field at point to sentence case: all words are lowercased except the first, which is capitalized. Words containing @LaTeX{} commands (@samp{$}, @samp{@{}, @samp{@}}, @samp{\}) are left untouched. This is useful for normalizing titles that were imported in title case.

The command @code{ebib-extras-update-field} fetches a fresh value for the field at point (or a specified field) from external sources using Zotero translators (via @code{zotra-extras-get-field}). The lookup is based on the entry's existing DOI, ISBN, or URL (@ref{Identifier retrieval}). The fetched value overwrites the current field contents.

The command @code{ebib-extras-set-abstract} populates the @samp{abstract} field for the entry at point (or a specified key) if it is currently empty. It uses @code{tlon-get-abstract-with-or-without-ai} to attempt fetching the abstract from external sources or generating it with AI@.

The command @code{ebib-extras-set-id} adds an identifier to the current entry when the appropriate field is empty. The field is chosen based on the entry's supertype: @samp{isbn} for books, @samp{doi} for articles, @samp{url} for films. If no ID is provided interactively, it attempts to fetch one using @code{ebib-extras-fetch-id-or-url} (@ref{Identifier retrieval}).

The command @code{ebib-extras-no-translation-found} sets the @samp{note} field to a message indicating that no translation was found, including the current date. It signals a user error if the @samp{note} field is already non-empty.

@node Language handling
@subsection Language handling

@findex ebib-extras-get-or-set-language
The command @code{ebib-extras-get-or-set-language} returns the language of the current entry from the @samp{langid} field. If the field is empty or contains an invalid language (one not found in @code{tlon-languages-properties}), it prompts the user to select a language using @code{completing-read}, defaulting to @samp{english}, and sets the field. The command adapts its behavior based on the current major mode: it uses @code{ebib-extras-get-field} and @code{ebib-extras-set-field} in @code{ebib-entry-mode}, and @code{bibtex-extras-get-field} and @code{bibtex-set-field} in @code{bibtex-mode}.

@node Keywords
@subsection Keywords

@findex ebib-extras-fetch-keywords
@findex ebib-extras-export-keywords
The command @code{ebib-extras-fetch-keywords} fetches keywords for the entry at point using @code{ebib-extras-fetch-field-value} and updates the @samp{keywords} field. This relies on external tools (via Zotero translators) to supply keyword data.

The command @code{ebib-extras-export-keywords} moves keywords from the Bib@TeX{} entry into the associated Org note file. It extracts the comma-separated keywords from the @samp{keywords} field, removes the field from the Bib@TeX{} entry, opens the associated note (via @code{ebib-extras-citar-open-notes}, see @ref{Notes integration}), creates a @samp{keywords} subheading, inserts the keywords as linkified elements (using @code{org-extras-linkify-elements}), and sorts them alphabetically (using @code{org-extras-sort-keywords}).

@node Ratings and notes
@subsection Ratings and notes

@findex ebib-extras-set-rating
@findex ebib-extras-no-translation-found
The command @code{ebib-extras-set-rating} prompts for a rating (1--10, where pressing @samp{0} means 10) and stores it in the @samp{rating} field. In addition to updating the Bib@TeX{} entry, it opens external rating websites based on the entry's supertype:

@itemize
@item
For books, it opens Goodreads with the entry's title.
@item
For films, it opens the entry's stored IMDb URL (or searches IMDb if no URL is stored) and opens Letterboxd (using a stored slug or fetching one via @code{bib-search-letterboxd}). If a Letterboxd slug is fetched, it is stored in the @samp{letterboxd} field for future use. The slug is always a bare identifier (e.g. @samp{hamnet-2025}), never a full URL@.
@end itemize

Pressing @samp{RET} without entering a digit skips the rating without modifying the field.

