@node DWIM search
@subsection DWIM search

@findex ebib-extras-search-dwim
The command @code{ebib-extras-search-dwim} performs context-sensitive searches. It examines the entry's supertype (book, article, or film) and the field at point to decide what to search for and where:

@itemize
@item
If the field at point is @samp{title}, it searches by title using the appropriate set of search functions for the supertype.
@item
If the field at point is anything else, it searches by identifier (DOI or ISBN).
@end itemize

The dispatch is handled by @code{ebib-extras--search-or-download}, which constructs the correct function name dynamically (e.g., @code{ebib-extras-search-book-by-title}).

@node Searching by title
@subsection Searching by title

@findex ebib-extras-search-book-by-title
@findex ebib-extras-search-article-by-title
@findex ebib-extras-search-film-by-title
Each of these commands retrieves the entry's title and opens search results on multiple websites simultaneously:

@itemize
@item
@code{ebib-extras-search-book-by-title} searches on Goodreads, HathiTrust, University of California Berkeley library, Internet Archive, Library Genesis, and Amazon. The list of functions is defined in @code{ebib-extras-search-book-functions} (@ref{Search engine constants}).
@item
@code{ebib-extras-search-article-by-title} searches on Connected Papers and Google Scholar, as defined in @code{ebib-extras-search-article-functions}.
@item
@code{ebib-extras-search-film-by-title} searches on IMDb, Letterboxd, and Metacritic, as defined in @code{ebib-extras-search-film-functions}.
@end itemize

For book entries, the title is retrieved from either the @samp{title} or @samp{booktitle} field (whichever is non-empty). If the title is empty, a user error is signaled.

@node Searching by identifier
@subsection Searching by identifier

@findex ebib-extras-search-by-identifier
The command @code{ebib-extras-search-by-identifier} searches for the entry using its ISBN or DOI@. It first checks the @samp{isbn} field (via @code{ebib-extras-get-isbn}), then falls back to the @samp{doi} field, and finally prompts the user for a manual identifier. If the identifier looks like an ISBN, it calls @code{ebib-extras-search-book}; if it looks like a DOI (via @code{annas-archive--doi-p}), it calls @code{ebib-extras-search-article}.

The aliases @code{ebib-extras-search-book-by-identifier} and @code{ebib-extras-search-article-by-identifier} both point to this command. The alias @code{ebib-extras-search-film-by-identifier} points to @code{ebib-extras-search-film-by-title} because films have no standard identifier.

@node Generated search commands
@subsection Generated search commands

@findex ebib-extras-generate-search-commands
@findex ebib-extras-search
Individual search commands for each search engine (e.g., @code{ebib-extras-search-goodreads}, @code{ebib-extras-search-google-scholar}, @code{ebib-extras-search-library-genesis}) are generated automatically by @code{ebib-extras-generate-search-commands}. This function iterates over @code{ebib-extras-search-engines} and creates a command for each one. Each generated command accepts an optional QUERY argument; when called interactively, it prompts for the search string. The generated commands call @code{ebib-extras-search}, which constructs a URL from the search engine's prefix, the URL-encoded query, and the engine's suffix, and opens it in the browser.

The search engines are defined as constants (@ref{Search engine constants}), each a list of three elements: a human-readable name, a URL prefix, and a URL suffix.

