@node Opening and switching
@subsection Opening and switching

@findex ebib-extras-open-or-switch
The command @code{ebib-extras-open-or-switch} opens Ebib in an appropriate window layout. It first splits the frame if it is currently unsplit (using @code{window-extras-split-if-unsplit}), then selects the second or third window (depending on frame width relative to @code{window-extras-frame-split-width-threshold}), and invokes @code{ebib}. If Ebib is already open, it switches to the existing Ebib window.

@node Sorting
@subsection Sorting

@findex ebib-extras-sort
The command @code{ebib-extras-sort} sorts the Ebib index buffer by a specified criterion, or cycles through the available criteria on successive calls. The sort states are defined in @code{ebib-extras-sort-states} (by default: Timestamp, Author, Title). When sorting by Timestamp, the order is descending (newest first); for all other criteria, the order is ascending.

The current sort state is tracked in the variable @code{ebib-extras-sort-state}, and each invocation advances to the next state in the cycle.

@node Navigation
@subsection Navigation

@findex ebib-extras-next-entry
@findex ebib-extras-prev-entry
@findex ebib-extras-end-of-index-buffer
The commands @code{ebib-extras-next-entry} and @code{ebib-extras-prev-entry} move to the next or previous entry in the current database. They work in both @code{ebib-index-mode} and @code{ebib-entry-mode}. When used in @code{ebib-entry-mode}, they switch to the index buffer, move to the adjacent entry, and then re-open the entry buffer---effectively navigating between entries without leaving the entry view.

The command @code{ebib-extras-end-of-index-buffer} moves point to the last entry line in the Ebib index buffer. It is only active when the current buffer is in @code{ebib-index-mode}.

@node Duplicating entries
@subsection Duplicating entries

@findex ebib-extras-duplicate-entry
The command @code{ebib-extras-duplicate-entry} creates a copy of the entry at point. It prompts for the target bibliography file (via @code{zotra-extras-set-bibfile}), generates a unique key if @code{ebib-uniquify-keys} is non-nil, inserts the formatted entry into the target file, updates the timestamp, reloads the database, and opens the new entry in Ebib. The index is sorted by Timestamp (descending) so the new entry appears at the top.

@node Saving and reloading databases
@subsection Saving and reloading databases

@findex ebib-extras-auto-save-databases
@findex ebib-extras-auto-reload-databases
@findex ebib-extras-auto-reload-database
@findex ebib-extras-reload-all-databases
@findex ebib-extras-reload-database-no-confirm
@findex ebib-extras-remove-file-notify-watchers
The function @code{ebib-extras-auto-save-databases} checks all Ebib databases for modifications and saves any that have been changed. It re-schedules itself via @code{run-with-timer} to run again after one second, creating a continuous auto-save loop. This function is called automatically when the file is loaded.

The command @code{ebib-extras-auto-reload-databases} sets up file-notify watchers on all database files so that when a file changes on disk (e.g., from an external edit or a sync), the corresponding Ebib database is automatically reloaded. It first removes any existing watchers (via @code{ebib-extras-remove-file-notify-watchers}) and then establishes a new watcher for each database using @code{ebib-extras-auto-reload-database}.

The reload callback includes a 10-second cooldown per database file (tracked in @code{ebib-extras-last-reload-times}) to prevent rapid consecutive reloads from file sync systems like Dropbox.

The command @code{ebib-extras-reload-all-databases} reloads all databases at once, but only if no database buffer is currently modified (checked via @code{ebib-extras-no-db-modified-p}). It initializes Ebib if it has not been initialized yet. This is useful for forced reloads after bulk edits.

The function @code{ebib-extras-reload-database-no-confirm} reloads a single database without prompting for confirmation (unless the database has unsaved modifications, in which case it does prompt). It preserves the current entry key and is used internally by the auto-reload mechanism.

@node Browsing URLs and DOIs
@subsection Browsing URLs and DOIs

@findex ebib-extras-browse-url-or-doi
The command @code{ebib-extras-browse-url-or-doi} opens the entry's URL in the browser. If the entry has a @samp{letterboxd} field with a slug, it also opens the Letterboxd page (using @code{bib-letterboxd-url} as the URL template). If no @samp{url} field is present, it falls back to the @samp{doi} field (calling @code{ebib-browse-doi}). If neither is available, it signals a user error.

@node Looking up entries and opening in Ebib
@subsection Looking up entries and opening in Ebib

@findex ebib-extras-get-or-open-entry
@findex ebib-extras-open-key
@findex ebib-extras-get-file-of-key
The command @code{ebib-extras-get-or-open-entry} opens the Bib@TeX{} source file for the current entry and positions point on the entry. When called interactively (with INTERACTIVE-P non-nil), it visits the file in a buffer. When called programmatically, it returns the entry as a string (via @code{bibtex-extras-get-entry-as-string}) without displaying the buffer.

The command @code{ebib-extras-open-key} opens the entry for a given KEY in Ebib. It first locates the bibliography file containing the key (via @code{ebib-extras-get-file-of-key}), then invokes @code{ebib} with the file and key, and opens the entry buffer. This is used internally to navigate to specific entries from other contexts.

The function @code{ebib-extras-get-file-of-key} searches all loaded Ebib databases (as listed in @code{paths-files-bibliography-all}) for the given KEY and returns the filename of the database that contains it. It signals a user error if Ebib has not been launched yet.

@node Author checking
@subsection Author checking

@findex ebib-extras-check-author-exists
@findex ebib-extras-create-list-of-existing-authors
The command @code{ebib-extras-check-author-exists} checks whether the @samp{author} field of the current entry matches any author already present in the database. This is useful for spotting variant spellings or new authors. It relies on @code{ebib-extras-existing-authors}, which must first be populated by calling @code{ebib-extras-create-list-of-existing-authors}. That function uses @code{ebib--create-author/editor-collection} to build the list from the current database.

@node Notes integration
@section Notes integration

@findex ebib-extras-citar-open-notes
The command @code{ebib-extras-citar-open-notes} opens the Org note associated with the current entry using @code{citar-open-notes}. This replaces the native @code{ebib-popup-note} command. The key difference is that when a note does not already exist, it is created following the same schema as notes created through @samp{citar}, ensuring consistency in note file naming and metadata across the bibliography.

@node PDF metadata
@section PDF metadata

@findex ebib-extras-set-pdf-metadata
@findex ebib-extras-ocr-pdf
The command @code{ebib-extras-set-pdf-metadata} writes Author and Title metadata into the PDF file associated with the current entry (or a specified key). It uses @samp{pdftk-java} (or @samp{pdftk} if available) to update the metadata in place. The author names are extracted and formatted from the Bib@TeX{} @samp{author} (or @samp{editor}) field using @code{ebib-extras-get-authors-list} and @code{ebib-extras-format-authors} (@ref{Author formatting}). The command signals a user error if @samp{pdftk-java} is not installed.

The command @code{ebib-extras-ocr-pdf} performs OCR on the PDF file associated with the current entry using @code{files-extras-ocr-pdf}. When called with a prefix argument (@samp{C-u}), OCR is forced even if text is already present in the PDF@.

@node Identifier retrieval
@section Identifier retrieval

@findex ebib-extras-get-id-or-url
@findex ebib-extras-fetch-id-or-url
@findex ebib-extras-get-or-fetch-id-or-url
The function @code{ebib-extras-get-id-or-url} returns the first available identifier from the current entry, checking the @samp{doi}, @samp{isbn}, and @samp{url} fields in that order. It adapts to both @code{ebib-entry-mode} and @code{bibtex-mode}.

The function @code{ebib-extras-fetch-id-or-url} attempts to fetch an identifier from external sources when none is available in the entry. It dispatches based on the entry's supertype: for books, it calls @code{bib-search-isbn}; for articles, @code{bib-search-crossref}; for films, @code{bib-search-imdb} (after translating the title to English). If the supertype is unrecognized, it falls back to the @samp{url} field.

The function @code{ebib-extras-get-or-fetch-id-or-url} combines both: it first tries to get an existing identifier, and if that fails, it fetches one.

