@node File retrieval
@section File retrieval

@findex ebib-extras-get-file
@findex ebib-extras-get-file-in-string
@findex ebib-extras-get-text-file
The function @code{ebib-extras-get-file} returns the path of the file with a given EXTENSION from the @samp{file} field of the entry at point. It adapts to the current major mode (@code{ebib-entry-mode} or @code{bibtex-mode}) to determine the correct field-access function. Returns @code{nil} if no matching file is found.

The function @code{ebib-extras-get-file-in-string} is the lower-level helper that searches a semicolon-separated file string for a file with the given EXTENSION@.

The function @code{ebib-extras-get-text-file} returns the path of the first text file found for the entry at point, iterating through @code{ebib-extras-valid-text-file-extensions} (HTML, PDF, SRT, VTT) in order (@ref{File extension constants}).

@node Key validation
@section Key validation

@findex ebib-extras-key-is-valid-p
@findex ebib-extras-check-valid-key
The function @code{ebib-extras-key-is-valid-p} returns @code{t} if the given KEY (or the entry at point) matches @code{ebib-extras-valid-key-regexp} (@ref{Key validation pattern, , @code{ebib-extras-valid-key-regexp}}). The pattern requires alphanumeric characters, four consecutive digits (a year), and additional alphanumeric characters.

The function @code{ebib-extras-check-valid-key} signals a user error if the key is invalid, prompting the user to regenerate it. This is used as a guard in commands like @code{ebib-extras-attach-file} and @code{ebib-extras-rename-files}.

@node ISBN and entry type detection
@section ISBN and entry type detection

@findex ebib-extras-isbn-p
@findex ebib-extras-get-isbn
@findex ebib-extras-video-p
@findex ebib-extras-get-supertype
The function @code{ebib-extras-isbn-p} returns @code{t} if a STRING matches the ISBN pattern (10 or 13 digits, with optional hyphens and the ``ISBN'' prefix). The pattern is defined in the constant @code{ebib-extras-isbn-p} (the constant and the function share the same name).

The function @code{ebib-extras-get-isbn} extracts the ISBN from the entry with a given KEY (or the entry at point), strips hyphens, and returns only the first ISBN if multiple are listed.

The function @code{ebib-extras-video-p} returns @code{t} if a STRING matches a YouTube URL pattern.

The function @code{ebib-extras-get-supertype} determines the broad category of the current entry based on its type: @samp{book} for book-like types (as listed in @code{ebib-extras-book-like-entry-types}), @samp{article} for article-like types, or @samp{film} for film-like types (@ref{Entry type constants}).

@node Author formatting
@section Author formatting

@findex ebib-extras-get-authors-list
@findex ebib-extras-format-authors
@findex ebib-extras-unbrace
The function @code{ebib-extras-get-authors-list} splits an AUTHORS string (in Bib@TeX{} @samp{and}-separated format) into a list of individual author names. Names in ``Last, First'' format are reversed to ``First Last''. Names enclosed in braces (e.g., corporate authors like @samp{@{World Health Organization@}}) are left intact but the braces are removed.

The function @code{ebib-extras-format-authors} joins a list of author names into a single string. It accepts an optional SEPARATOR (defaulting to @samp{" & "}) and a MAX number of authors (defaulting to 3). When the number of authors exceeds MAX, only the first author is listed, followed by @samp{" et al"}.

The function @code{ebib-extras-unbrace} removes all curly braces from a string. Unlike @code{ebib-unbrace}, which removes only the outermost pair of braces, this function removes every brace in the string.

@node Field access helpers
@section Field access helpers

@findex ebib-extras-get-field
@findex ebib-extras-set-field
@findex ebib-extras-update-entry-buffer
The function @code{ebib-extras-get-field} is a convenience wrapper around @code{ebib-get-field-value}. It returns the value of FIELD for the entry with KEY (or the entry at point), with sensible defaults: errors are suppressed, braces are removed, cross-references are resolved, and line breaks and extra whitespace are collapsed to single spaces.

The function @code{ebib-extras-set-field} sets the value of FIELD to VALUE for the entry at point. It preserves the bracing status of the original field contents and updates the entry buffer display afterward.

The function @code{ebib-extras-update-entry-buffer} refreshes the Ebib entry buffer display after field modifications. It calls @code{ebib--update-entry-buffer}, clears the buffer's modified flag, and marks the database as modified, all wrapped in @code{save-excursion} so point is preserved.

@node Database utilities
@section Database utilities

@findex ebib-extras-get-db-number
@findex ebib-extras-no-db-modified-p
The function @code{ebib-extras-get-db-number} returns the predefined number associated with a database FILE path, as defined in @code{ebib-extras-db-numbers} (@ref{Database constants, , @code{ebib-extras-db-numbers}}). This is useful for commands that switch between databases by number.

The function @code{ebib-extras-no-db-modified-p} returns @code{t} if no Ebib database buffer is currently marked as modified. It is used as a guard by @code{ebib-extras-reload-all-databases} to prevent reloading while unsaved changes exist (@ref{Saving and reloading databases}).

